# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: key-management-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] A **key** in cryptography is a piece of information, usually a string of numbers or letters that are stored in a file, which, when processed through a cryptographic algorithm, can encode or decode cryptographic data.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Based on the used method, the key can be different sizes and varieties, but in all cases, the strength of the encryption relies on the security of the key being maintained.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] A key's security strength is dependent on its algorithm, the size of the key, the generation of the key, and the process of key exchange.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] The key is what is used to encrypt data from plaintext to ciphertext.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] There are different methods for utilizing keys and encryption.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Symmetric cryptography refers to the practice of the same key being used for both encryption and decryption.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Asymmetric cryptography has separate keys for encrypting and decrypting.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] These keys are known as the public and private keys, respectively.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Since the key protects the confidentiality and integrity of the system, it is important to be kept secret from unauthorized parties.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] With public key cryptography, only the private key must be kept secret, but with symmetric cryptography, it is important to maintain the confidentiality of the key.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Kerckhoff's principle states that the entire security of the cryptographic system relies on the secrecy of the key.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Key size is the number of bits in the key defined by the algorithm.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] This size defines the upper bound of the cryptographic algorithm's security.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] The larger the key size, the longer it will take before the key is compromised by a brute force attack.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Since perfect secrecy is not feasible for key algorithms, researches are now more focused on computational security.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] In the past, keys were required to be a minimum of 40 bits in length, however, as technology advanced, these keys were being broken quicker and quicker.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] As a response, restrictions on symmetric keys were enhanced to be greater in size.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Currently, 2048 bit RSA is commonly used, which is sufficient for current systems.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] However, current RSA key sizes would all be cracked quickly with a powerful quantum computer.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] "The keys used in public key cryptography have some mathematical structure.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] For example, public keys used in the RSA system are the product of two prime numbers.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Thus public key systems require longer key lengths than symmetric systems for an equivalent level of security.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] To prevent a key from being guessed, keys need to be generated randomly and contain sufficient entropy.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] The problem of how to safely generate random keys is difficult and has been addressed in many ways by various cryptographic systems.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] A key can directly be generated by using the output of a Random Bit Generator (RBG), a system that generates a sequence of unpredictable and unbiased bits.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] A RBG can be used to directly produce either a symmetric key or the random output for an asymmetric key pair generation.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Alternatively, a key can also be indirectly created during a key-agreement transaction, from another key or from a password.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Some operating systems include tools for "collecting" entropy from the timing of unpredictable operations such as disk drive head movements.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] For the production of small amounts of keying material, ordinary dice provide a good source of high-quality randomness.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] The security of a key is dependent on how a key is exchanged between parties.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Establishing a secured communication channel is necessary so that outsiders cannot obtain the key.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] A key establishment scheme (or key exchange) is used to transfer an encryption key among entities.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Key agreement and key transport are the two types of a key exchange scheme that are used to be remotely exchanged between entities .
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] In a key agreement scheme, a secret key, which is used between the sender and the receiver to encrypt and decrypt information, is set up to be sent indirectly.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] All parties exchange information (the shared secret) that permits each party to derive the secret key material.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] In a key transport scheme, encrypted keying material that is chosen by the sender is transported to the receiver.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Either symmetric key or asymmetric key techniques can be used in both schemes.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] The Diffie–Hellman key exchange and Rivest-Shamir-Adleman (RSA) are the most two widely used key exchange algorithms.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman constructed the Diffie–Hellman algorithm, which was the first public key algorithm.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] The Diffie–Hellman key exchange protocol allows key exchange over an insecure channel by electronically generating a shared key between two parties.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] On the other hand, RSA is a form of the asymmetric key system which consists of three steps: key generation, encryption, and decryption.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Key confirmation delivers an assurance between the key confirmation recipient and provider that the shared keying materials are correct and established.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends key confirmation to be integrated into a key establishment scheme to validate its implementations.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Key management concerns the generation, establishment, storage, usage and replacement of cryptographic keys.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] A key management system (KMS) typically includes three steps of establishing, storing and using keys.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] The base of security for the generation, storage, distribution, use and destruction of keys depends on successful key management protocols.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] A password is a memorized series of characters including letters, digits, and other special symbols that are used to verify identity.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] It is often produced by a human user or a password management software to protect personal and sensitive information or generate cryptographic keys.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Passwords are often created to be memorized by users and may contain non-random information such as dictionary words.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] On the other hand, a key can help strengthen password protection by implementing a cryptographic algorithm which is difficult to guess or replace the password altogether.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] A key is generated based on random or pseudo-random data and can often be unreadable to humans.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] A password is less safe than a cryptographic key due to its low entropy, randomness, and human-readable properties.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] However, the password may be the only secret data that is accessible to the cryptographic algorithm for information security in some applications such as securing information in storage devices.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Thus, a deterministic algorithm called a key derivation function (KDF) uses a password to generate the secure cryptographic keying material to compensate for the password's weakness.
[src:key-management-deep/key-cryptography] Various methods such as adding a salt or key stretching may be used in the generation.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] In cryptography, a **key derivation function** (**KDF**) is a cryptographic algorithm that derives one or more secret keys from a secret value such as a master key, a password, or a passphrase using a pseudorandom function (which typically uses a cryptographic hash function or block cipher).
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] KDFs can be used to stretch keys into longer keys or to obtain keys of a required format, such as converting a group element that is the result of a Diffie–Hellman key exchange into a symmetric key for use with AES.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Keyed cryptographic hash functions are popular examples of pseudorandom functions used for key derivation.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] The first deliberately slow (key stretching) password-based key derivation function was called "crypt" (or "crypt(3)" after its man page), and was invented by Robert Morris in 1978.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] It would encrypt a constant (zero), using the first 8 characters of the user's password as the key, by performing 25 iterations of a modified DES encryption algorithm (in which a 12-bit number read from the real-time computer clock is used to perturb the calculations).
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] The resulting 64-bit number is encoded as 11 printable characters and then stored in the Unix password file.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] While it was a great advance at the time, increases in processor speeds since the PDP-11 era have made brute-force attacks against crypt feasible, and advances in storage have rendered the 12-bit salt inadequate.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] The crypt function's design also limits the user password to 8 characters, which limits the keyspace and makes strong passphrases impossible.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Although high throughput is a desirable property in general-purpose hash functions, the opposite is true in password security applications in which defending against brute-force cracking is a primary concern.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Various algorithms have been designed specifically for this purpose, including bcrypt, scrypt and, more recently, Lyra2 and Argon2 (the latter being the winner of the Password Hashing Competition).
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] The large-scale Ashley Madison data breach in which roughly 36 million passwords hashes were stolen by attackers illustrated the importance of algorithm selection in securing passwords.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) issued a new revision of their digital authentication guidelines, NIST SP 800-63B-3, stating that: "Verifiers SHALL store memorized secrets [i.e. passwords] in a form that is resistant to offline attacks.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Memorized secrets SHALL be salted and hashed using a suitable one-way key derivation function.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions take a password, a salt, and a cost factor as inputs then generate a password hash.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Modern password-based key derivation functions, such as PBKDF2, are based on a recognized cryptographic hash, such as SHA-2, use more salt (at least 64 bits and chosen randomly) and a high iteration count.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] NIST recommends a minimum iteration count of 10,000.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] The original use for a KDF is key derivation, the generation of keys from secret passwords or passphrases.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Key derivation functions are also used in applications to derive keys from secret passwords or passphrases, which typically do not have the desired properties to be used directly as cryptographic keys.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] In such applications, it is generally recommended that the key derivation function be made deliberately slow so as to frustrate brute-force attack or dictionary attack on the password or passphrase input value.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Such use may be expressed as DK = KDF(key, salt, iterations), where DK is the derived key, KDF is the key derivation function, key is the original key or password, salt is a random number which acts as cryptographic salt, and iterations refers to the number of iterations of a sub-function.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] The derived key is used instead of the original key or password as the key to the system.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] The values of the salt and the number of iterations (if it is not fixed) are stored with the hashed password or sent as cleartext (unencrypted) with an encrypted message.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] The difficulty of a brute force attack is increased with the number of iterations.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] A practical limit on the iteration count is the unwillingness of users to tolerate a perceptible delay in logging into a computer or seeing a decrypted message.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] The use of salt prevents the attackers from precomputing a dictionary of derived keys.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] An alternative approach, called **key strengthening**, extends the key with a random salt, but then (unlike in key stretching) securely deletes the salt.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] This forces both the attacker and legitimate users to perform a brute-force search for the salt value.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Although the paper that introduced key stretching referred to this earlier technique and intentionally chose a different name, the term "key strengthening" is now often (arguably incorrectly) used to refer to key stretching.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Despite their original use for key derivation, KDFs are possibly better known for their use in **password hashing** (password verification by hash comparison), as used by the passwd file or shadow password file.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Password hash functions should be relatively expensive to calculate in case of brute-force attacks, and KDFs are designed with this characteristic built in.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] The non-secret parameters are called "salt" in this context.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] In 2013 a Password Hashing Competition was announced to choose a new, standard algorithm for password hashing.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] On 20 July 2015 the competition ended and Argon2 was announced as the final winner.
[src:key-management-deep/key-derivation-function] Four other algorithms received special recognition: Catena, Lyra2, Makwa and yescrypt.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] The technical problem is a largely structural one.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] Access to protected information must be provided *only* to the intended recipient and at least one third party.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] The third party should be permitted access only under carefully controlled conditions, for instance, a court order.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] Thus far, no system design has been shown to meet this requirement fully on a technical basis alone.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] All proposed systems also require correct functioning of some social linkage, for instance the process of request for access, examination of request for 'legitimacy' (as by a court), and granting of access by technical personnel charged with access control.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] All such linkages / controls have serious problems from a system design security perspective.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] Systems in which the key may not be changed easily are rendered especially vulnerable as the accidental release of the key will result in many devices becoming totally compromised, necessitating an immediate key change or replacement of the system.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] On a national level, key escrow is controversial in many countries for at least two reasons.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] One involves mistrust of the security of the structural escrow arrangement.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] Many countries have a long history of less than adequate protection of others' information by assorted organizations, public and private, even when the information is held only under an affirmative legal obligation to protect it from unauthorized access.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] Another is technical concerns for the additional vulnerabilities likely to be introduced by supporting key escrow operations.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] Thus far, no key escrow system has been designed which meets both objections and nearly all have failed to meet even one.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] Key escrow is proactive, anticipating the need for access to keys; a retroactive alternative is key disclosure law, where users are required to surrender keys upon demand by law enforcement, or else face legal penalties.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] Key disclosure law avoids some of the technical issues and risks of key escrow systems, but also introduces new risks like loss of keys and legal issues such as involuntary self-incrimination.
[src:key-management-deep/key-escrow] The ambiguous term *key recovery* is applied to both types of systems.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] If the sender and receiver wish to exchange encrypted messages, each must be equipped to encrypt messages to be sent and decrypt messages received.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] The nature of the equipping they require depends on the encryption technique they might use.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] If they use a code, both will require a copy of the same codebook.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] If they use a cipher, they will need appropriate keys.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] If the cipher is a symmetric key cipher, both will need a copy of the same key.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] If it is an asymmetric key cipher with the public/private key property, both will need the other's public key.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Key exchange is done either in-band or out-of-band.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] The key exchange problem describes ways to exchange whatever keys or other information are needed for establishing a secure communication channel so that no one else can obtain a copy.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Historically, before the invention of public-key cryptography (asymmetrical cryptography), symmetric-key cryptography utilized a single key to encrypt and decrypt messages.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] For two parties to communicate confidentially, they must first exchange the secret key so that each party is able to encrypt messages before sending, and decrypt received ones.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] This process is known as the key exchange.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] The overarching problem with symmetrical cryptography, or single-key cryptography, is that it requires a secret key to be communicated through trusted couriers, diplomatic bags, or any other secure communication channel.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] If two parties cannot establish a secure initial key exchange, they won't be able to communicate securely without the risk of messages being intercepted and decrypted by a third party who acquired the key during the initial key exchange.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Public-key cryptography uses a two-key system, consisting of the public and the private keys, where messages are encrypted with one key and decrypted with another.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] It depends on the selected cryptographic algorithm which key—public or private—is used for encrypting messages, and which for decrypting.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] For example, in RSA, the private key is used for decrypting messages, while in the Digital Signature Algorithm (DSA), the private key is used for authenticating them.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] The public key can be sent over non-secure channels or shared in public; the private key is only available to its owner.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Known as the Diffie-Hellman key exchange, the encryption key can be openly communicated as it poses no risk to the confidentiality of encrypted messages.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] One party exchanges the keys to another party where they can then encrypt messages using the key and send back the cipher text.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Only the decryption key—in this case, it's the private key—can decrypt that message.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] At no time during the Diffie-Hellman key exchange is any sensitive information at risk of compromise, as opposed to symmetrical key exchange.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] In principle, the only remaining problem was to be sure (or at least confident) that a public key actually belonged to its supposed owner.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Because it is possible to 'spoof' another's identity in any of several ways, this is not a trivial or easily solved problem, particularly when the two users involved have never met and know nothing about each other.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman published a cryptographic protocol called the Diffie–Hellman key exchange (D–H) based on concepts developed by Hellman's PhD student Ralph Merkle.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] The protocol enables users to securely exchange secret keys even if an opponent is monitoring that communication channel.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] The D–H key exchange protocol, however, does not by itself address authentication (i.e. the problem of being sure of the actual identity of the person or 'entity' at the other end of the communication channel).
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Authentication is crucial when an opponent can both monitor *and alter* messages within the communication channel (AKA man-in-the-middle or MITM attacks) and was addressed in the fourth section of the paper.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Public key infrastructures (PKIs) have been proposed as a workaround for the problem of identity authentication.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] In their most usual implementation, each user applies to a “certificate authority” (CA), trusted by all parties, for a digital certificate which serves for other users as a non-tamperable authentication of identity.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] The infrastructure is safe, unless the CA itself is compromised.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] In case it is, though, many PKIs provide a way to revoke certificates so other users will not trust them.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Revoked certificates are usually put in certificate revocation lists which any certificate can be matched against.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Several countries and other jurisdictions have passed legislation or issued regulations encouraging PKIs by giving (more or less) legal effect to these digital certificates (see digital signature).
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Many commercial firms, as well as a few government departments, have established such certificate authorities.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] This does nothing to solve the problem though, as the trustworthiness of the CA itself is still not guaranteed for any particular individual.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] It is a form of argument from authority fallacy.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] For actual trustworthiness, personal verification that the certificate belongs to the CA and establishment of trust in the CA are required.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] For those new to such things, these arrangements are best thought of as electronic notary endorsements that “this public key belongs to this user”.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] As with notary endorsements, there can be mistakes or misunderstandings in such vouchings.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Additionally, the notary itself can be untrusted.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] There have been several high-profile public failures by assorted certificate authorities.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] At the other end of the conceptual range is the web of trust system, which avoids central Certificate Authorities entirely.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Each user is responsible for getting a certificate from another user before using that certificate to communicate with the user.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] PGP and GPG (an implementation of the OpenPGP Internet Standard) employ just such a web of trust mechanism.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Password-authenticated key agreement algorithms can perform a cryptographic key exchange utilizing knowledge of a user's password.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Quantum key distribution exploits certain properties of quantum physics to ensure its security.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] It relies on the fact that observations (or measurements) of a quantum state introduces perturbations in that state.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Over many systems, these perturbations are detectable as noise by the receiver, making it possible to detect man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:key-management-deep/key-exchange] Beside the correctness and completeness of quantum mechanics, the protocol assumes the availability of an authenticated channel between Alice and Bob.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] A device or program used to generate keys is called a key generator or keygen.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] Modern cryptographic systems include symmetric-key algorithms (such as DES and AES) and public-key algorithms (such as RSA).
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] Symmetric-key algorithms use a single shared key; keeping data secret requires keeping this key secret.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] Public-key algorithms use a public key and a private key.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] The public key is made available to anyone (often by means of a digital certificate).
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] A sender encrypts data with the receiver's public key; only the holder of the private key can decrypt this data.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] Since public-key algorithms tend to be much slower than symmetric-key algorithms, modern systems such as TLS and SSH use a combination of the two: one party receives the other's public key, and encrypts a small piece of data (either a symmetric key or some data used to generate it).
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] The remainder of the conversation uses a (typically faster) symmetric-key algorithm for encryption.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] Computer cryptography uses integers for keys.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] In some cases, keys are randomly generated using a *random number generator (RNG)* or *pseudorandom number generator (PRNG)*.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] A PRNG is a computer algorithm that produces data that appears random under analysis.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] PRNGs that use system entropy to seed data generally produce better results, since this makes the initial conditions of the PRNG much more difficult for an attacker to guess.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] Another way to generate randomness is to utilize information outside the system.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] Veracrypt (a disk encryption software) utilizes user mouse movements to generate unique seeds, in which users are encouraged to move their mouse sporadically.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] In other situations, the key is derived deterministically using a passphrase and a key derivation function.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] Many modern protocols are designed to have forward secrecy, which requires generating a fresh new shared key for each session.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] Classic cryptosystems invariably generate two identical keys at one end of the communication link and somehow transport one of the keys to the other end of the link.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] However, it simplifies key management to use Diffie–Hellman key exchange instead.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] The simplest method to read encrypted data without actually decrypting it is a brute-force attack—simply attempting every number, up to the maximum length of the key.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] Therefore, it is important to use a sufficiently long key length; longer keys take exponentially longer to attack, rendering a brute-force attack impractical.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] Currently, key lengths of 128 bits (for symmetric key algorithms) and 2048 bits (for public-key algorithms) are common.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] A wireless channel is characterized by its two end users.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] By transmitting pilot signals, these two users can estimate the channel between them and use the channel information to generate a key which is secret only to them.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] The common secret key for a group of users can be generated based on the channel of each pair of users.
[src:key-management-deep/key-generation] A key can also be generated by exploiting the phase fluctuation in a fiber link.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:key-management-deep/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
